<p>From Lee Sallows:</p>
<p>&#8220;In his book <a href="https://archive.org/details/amusementsinmath00dude/page/120/mode/2up"><em>Amusements in Mathematics</em></a>, H.E. Dudeney presents a method of classifying 4&#215;4 magic squares based on the distribution of their 8 complementary pairs 1 &#038; 16, 2 &#038; 15, .., 8 &#038; 9. There are just 12 distinct such distributions or &#8216;graphic types&#8217;, which he labelled I to XII. The square above is an example of a type X square.&#8221;</p>
<p>(Thanks, Lee.)</p>
